Borrowed from {{bor|en|frm|faction}}, from {{der|en|la|factiō||a group of people acting together, a political faction}}, noun of process from perfect passive participle {{m|la|factus}}, from {{m|la|faciō||do, make}}. {{doublet|en|fashion}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|countable}} A group of people, especially within a political organization, which expresses a [[shared]] [[belief]] or [[opinion]] different from people who are not part of the group.
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Essays, Moral and Political|author=[[w:David Hume|David Hume]]|year=1748|chapter=Of Parties in General — How '''factions''' arise and contend.|passage=Real '''factions''' may be divided into those from interest, from principle, and from affection}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[strife|Strife]]; [[discord]].
#* '''1805''', Johann Georg Cleminius, ''Englisches Lesebuch für Kaufleute'', [http://books.google.com/books?id=B9cRAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA188&dq=faction&lr=&num=100&as_brr=3 pg. 188]:
#*: Publick [sic] affairs soon fell into the utmost confusion, and in this state of '''faction''' and perplexity, the island continued, until its re-capture by the French in 1779.
#* '''2001''', Odd Magne Bakke, ''"Concord and Peace": A Rhetorical Analysis of the First Letter of Clement With an Emphasis on the Language of Unity and Sedition'', publ. Mohr Siebeck, {{ISBN|3161476379}}, [http://books.google.com/books?id=cI1btFqWegoC&pg=PA89&dq=%22faction%22&as_brr=3&sig=R6XBNzJrKPdhILpQQfGC22KlIgc pg. 89]:
#*: He asks the audience if they believe that they will be more loved by the gods if the city is in a state of '''faction''' than if they govern the city with good order and concord.

